explanation:
$\pmb{\text{Step 1: Calculate the Mass Defect}}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{Q} &=\left(\mathrm{m}_{\mathrm{N}}+\mathrm{m}_{\mathrm{He}}-\mathrm{m}_{\mathrm{H}}-\mathrm{m}_{\mathrm{O}}\right) \times \mathrm{c}^{2} \\
&=(16.006+4.003-1.008-19.003) \times 930 \mathrm{MeV} \\
&=-1.86 \mathrm{MeV} \\
&=1.86 \mathrm{MeV} \text { energy absorbed. }
\end{aligned}
$$

$\pmb{\text{Step 2: Calculate the Maximum Loss in Kinetic Energy}}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{m \times 4 m}{5 m} \times v^{2} &=\text{max loss in kinetic energy} \\
\Rightarrow \frac{1}{2} m v^{2} &=\frac{5}{4} \times Q \\
&=\frac{5}{4} \times(1.86) \mathrm{MeV} \\
&=2.325 \mathrm{MeV}
\end{aligned}
$$

$\pmb{\text{Step 3: Find the Value of n}}$

Therefore, the value of $n$ is $\boxed{2.325}$.
